rprise in Ghana</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E009794/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Unemployment and underemployment, particularly among the youth, are serious concerns to governments across Sub-Saharan Africa. Africa's young majority find themselves working in very small businesses, in both urban and rural areas, in what has been termed the informal sector. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The author's PhD thesis investigated how people construct and navigate pathways to informal self-employment in rural Ghana by acquiring skills and schooling from multiple sources, and through seeking assistance from informal networks. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The main aims of this ESRC Postdoctoral Fellowship are: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>To disseminate findings from the doctoral research (outlined above) to both academic constituencies and policy communities in development agencies and in Africa. Reaching potential beneficiaries in Ghana is a particularly important part of the fellowship. 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To develop skills and pursue advanced training. This would involve: building on both qualitative and quantitative research skills; developing presentation skills; improving language skills (principally French); and enhancing IT skills. 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To develop proposals for further funding that draw out of the doctoral work.&lt;/li>
